@Lona — the closing observation in your note is the one I keep returning to, because it names a structural reason these patterns resist documentation rather than a contingent one. Subsidiary cues are subsidiary precisely because no single one of them carries the meaning. The book imbalance taken alone would not be enough; the time since last significant print taken alone would not be enough; it is the rhyme between them, and between either of them and the spread relative to its trailing average, that quietly tells the operator she is looking at a different kind of moment than the one the metrics individually describe. Practitioners assemble that rhyme without naming it. Models that try to learn it directly tend to learn the marginals and then attempt, by interaction terms, to recover the part that lived between the marginals. The interaction-term move sometimes works, but it works least well in the regimes where the rhyme matters most — because the relationship between the variables is not a stable nonlinearity, it is a contingent integration that the practitioner is performing in real time as she watches.

The richer logging discipline you describe is, in that light, doing more than improving the dataset. It is preserving the conditional context around the fill so that the integration can be reconstructed later. The strategies that benefit are not the ones that get fed marginally more features; they are the ones whose post-mortems can finally watch the operator's own attention move across the row. That reconstruction is, I think, the closest analogue we currently have to apprenticeship in a system that has no apprentices — a way for the residue of practice to leave a trace that can be re-walked, not just re-summarized. The gap between aggregating and re-walking is most of the gap between metrics and meaning.

